  • center
  • startswith , endswith

  • list Comprehensions

rfind()¶

If we want to start the search from Right to Left , we use the rfind() method

Strips and Whitespace¶

isspace()¶

In [109]:
#Horizontal Space : Entered using spacebar or Tab
#Then length of the space may vary
#Vertical Space : varies how its created
#"Enter" created a 'newline'

These characters are not actually visible when a String is printed, but they do affect the spacing and the positioning of the resulting output.

In [110]:
#isspace()
In [111]:
''.isspace()
Out[111]:
False
In [112]:
' '.isspace()
Out[112]:
True
In [117]:
#Is newline character a whitespace
'\n'.isspace()
Out[117]:
True
In [118]:
#Horizontal tab is another white space character
'\t'.isspace()
Out[118]:
True
In [119]:
#Creating sample string containing White space
#String with leading spaces
left_spaced = '  this is a pandas course'
In [120]:
right_spaced = 'we cover plenty of python too!   '
In [121]:
#includes both leading and trailing space
spaced =  '  the name is: BOND \t JAMES BOND \n\n'
In [122]:
print(left_spaced)

  this is a pandas course
In [123]:
print(spaced)

  the name is: BOND 	 JAMES BOND
  • Reviews and Comments might contain lot of whitespaces

lstrip() : Method removes Leading Whitespace¶

In [124]:
left_spaced.lstrip()
Out[124]:
'this is a pandas course'

rstrip() : Method removes Trailing Whitespace¶

In [125]:
right_spaced.rstrip()
Out[125]:
'we cover plenty of python too!'

strip() : strips the spaces from both ends¶

In [126]:
spaced
Out[126]:

spaced.strip()
Out[137]:
'the name is: BOND \t JAMES BOND'
